            <span id="ChapterParagraphOne">
            <span id="BigFirstLetterText"></span>After our marriage in the Idaho Falls Temple, Ken and I went on a honeymoon trip to southern Utah and California. No, not in the green pickup! Ken's Dad let us use his car for that special trip! When we returned we lived in an apartment in Idaho Falls and I continued to work in the doctor's office until January when we moved out to the Milo farm. Ken owned 80 acres of farm ground and we began to purchase an adjoining 80 acres from his Dad, giving us 160 acres to begin our life as the farmer and his wife! <br /><br />

            In the fall of that first year we wanted another vehicle so we made the choice to travel to Detroit to pick the car up ourselves so we boarded the Greyhound bus and went to the big city. The trip was quite an adventure for these two farm people! We got to see a bit of Chicago and then went on to get the Oldsmobile 88, quite a terrific car those days, we saw some of NYC and visited Niagara Falls and then on down the east coast, travelling through Maryland on one of the very first freeways in the country, the Maryland Parkway. We traveled to Texas and visited my sister Melba and her family, and then on home. Quite a trip for two young and inexperienced Idahoans! <br /><br />
 
            The winter of 1948-1949 was severe with huge amounts of snow and very cold. We were “snowed-in” for about ten days shortly after we moved there. The roads were narrow and lower somewhat than the adjoining fields so the snow was continually blown and then piled into the road. The only way we could travel anywhere if the snow plow hadn't been in the area to “plow us out” was to walk. When the plows did come, the roads were usually one lane and the snow plowed high on the side of the road
            so high that we could touch the phone wires. I remember that Uncle Jack dug a tunnel from their front door out to their mailbox, so when the mail car could get through, that’s how they got to their mail box. Our farm bordered the county line road and when it was plowed out only one vehicle could travel at a time in one direction. <br /><br />

            We walked or rode Ken's white horse, Princess, about a half mile north to Aunt Mary's and Uncle Jack's. When we were able to get into Idaho Falls for supplies we had to use a sleigh part way down the Milo road and then were given a ride to the city. Quite an adventure that winter. No television, only books to read and games to play. We had the one horse and a Jersey cow. When the roads allowed us to get into Rigby, our favorite entertainment about once a week was at the movies. <br /><br />
             
            Early that first spring we “brooded' chicks in a basement room and when they were big enough to be marketed we set up in the backyard to slaughter them and de-feather and prepare to be sold. It was quite a process to de-feather so Uncle Jack came to help while Ken was doing fieldwork. This was the summer of 1949 and we were expecting our first baby to arrive later that month. During the process with the chickens, I mentioned to Uncle Jack that my baby would probably arrive that night, a couple weeks early. Uncle Jack said, “Oh probably not, too soon,” but sure enough Mike made his appearance that night (skinning chickens is hard work!). Our first son arrived at the LDS hospital in Idaho Falls on July 13, 1949. 


            </span>

