            <span id="ChapterParagraphOne">
            <span id="BigFirstLetterText"></span>
               That first year at the farm was really a learning experience for me. I learned how to clean eggs, how to kill and clean small chickens for market, how to skim cream off the top of the milk and how to run fast enough to keep the milk cows out of the yard, how to climb down into the well and flip the switch when the well went off and there was no water and I remember the fun Ken had when he was trying to teach me to milk a cow before there were milker machines—he didn’t succeed, by the way—I never did milk a cow by hand, but I did later milk with the milker machines (about 30 or 40 days in all, evening or morning). If Ken was in the field then the milking was for me and the boys, I remember the fun and the fear involved in learning how to drive a tractor and how angry a husband can get when his wife drives through a gate and doesn’t close it behind her and a whole herd of cows end up in the hay. <br /><br />

                One difficult lesson for me to learn throughout the years that we lived on the farm was that the farm work always had to come first, short of sickness; the chores had to be done, the crops had to be put in when it was time, they had to be irrigated, cultivated and harvested when it was “the season thereof” and that everything else had to wait on those times. It took me a few years to learn this and I can remember a few unhappy times while my young husband was trying to teach me. 

                    
            </span>

