            <span id="ChapterParagraphOne">
            <span id="BigFirstLetterText"></span>
            Being a nurse, I guess that has made me much more conscious of cleanliness, germs, dirt, and necessity for order and all kinds of other qualities. These parts of my personality and character have developed throughout my life and sometimes they have been “thorns in my side.” At other times, though, they have saved us much sorrow and discomfort. Anyway, having lived in the farm atmosphere has made me realize that as I look back, that perhaps I have been too fusty and then maybe at other times not careful enough. I often wonder how we managed to keep all our health as good as we have—the whole family of us. Farm living had its problems for me and it was difficult for me to handle the disorganization of the farm yards and the old, tumble-down buildings as so many of them were. We did build and add as we lived there and improved the appearance of the yards and buildings as best we could. <br /><br />

            Ken wasn’t too concerned about it, probably because his prime concern and responsibility was feeding all of us, which he did very well and that occupied most of his time during those years in Milo. The lawn mowing and caring for the garden, washing the car, etc. etc. all fell to my responsibility and I guess I did the best I could, begrudgingly at times but all in all I tried. I used to look out the kitchen window of that farmhouse and wish and wish that it was in better order and repair but knowing that I couldn’t do it myself so I tried to live with it. Many times I would spend hours and sometimes days cleaning out a shed or the shop just to have it back in shambles again within the month. I have fond memories of the day we burned down the old machine shop building. It faced the driveway and was always an eyesore. We burned it down after a number of years at the farm…hurrah! <br /><br />

            I longed for a hose and sprinkler to water the lawn instead of having it flood irrigated from a ditch that ran from up at the head of Ronald’s ground. But that was the method of watering the lawn, and the ditch water carried “millions and millions” of weed seed right onto our grass and garden areas around the house. It was always a summer long fight to get the weeds. But the kids loved the days when the lawn was to be flood irrigated because it supplied for them lots of water to romp in and they loved the instant pools provided for them and delighted in playing in the water on those days. We had an orchard to the south of the house and had mostly apples and one pear tree. We realized a harvest of apples mostly, but the pear tree didn’t have much to offer. Ken always wanted a good orchard with lots of fruit, peaches as the favorite. <br /><br />

            Later on in Labelle, he was able to have a peach tree which produced so many peaches that they couldn’t mature and ripen well and I remember our harvest was only about a half dozen. Since then we just went to Utah for the peaches! One of the many problems at living in the country was having to contend with mice and we had our share in Milo. And as I went down to the fruit room in the old basement I always had a fear of finding something “more than just a mouse!” It was dark and musty down there and always a little scary. One day I opened the basement door which was right off the kitchen and saw a movement right on the top step by the door…a pretty good-sized animal! I immediately thought “rat” as I saw his tail…it was very long and “rat-like” and I almost collapsed in dread. I yelled for help as he scurried back down the steps and out of sight. We heard him and later found him among the empty fruit jars and Ken got rid of him and blessings upon blessings—it was a muskrat…not a “real rat” after all (there’s a big difference, you know!).<br /><br />

            The “fruit room” in the basement served as a fruit and storage room for us. It had a few shelves and one of the first things Ken did was to add shelves in that room so we would have plenty of space for putting canned fruits and vegetables on those shelves. This was the beginning of many, many hours spent canning food for our family during the years to come. We tried to raise some sort of a garden each year but mostly they weren’t that great. Ken was always so busy with farm work and I just didn’t have any heart to weed and keep a big garden in order. I guess it was the weeds; it was impossible for one person to keep the weeds out of that garden spot. I was sure it would take a frill crew working several hours a day to keep ahead of them and I guess it was because of the irrigating process. The ditch probably carried water that was frill of weed seed and it “dumped them all right on my garden spot” and it soon became impossible for me to keep them out. <br /><br />

            I longed for the day when we could use a garden hose and water from the well to water the garden but I don’t remember that ever happening at the farm because of the hardship it would be on the well. We canned the vegetables and raspberries we raised and usually had lots of tomatoes and carrots. I learned early in married life what a thrill it is to fill bottles with food and then seal them and put them on the shelves to be used later. My parents used to come to frequently to the farm and usually were on hand in the fell when we were canning peaches. <br /><br />

            After the boys grew old enough to help their dad in the fields and with the chores, their appetites grew and they loved to eat canned fruit: peaches mostly, and we usually put at least 200 quarts of peaches on the shelves each fall. We often made a trip to Utah especially to get the fruit, so it was fun as well as hard work. I found out very soon in married life at that farm that farm living was not as easy as living in a city. I had been raised as the last of a large family and had not been required to do very much hard work but I soon learned that in order to keep a house and hearth functioning it required a lot of hard work and perseverance. <br /><br />

            I had always enjoyed having an orderly home with “a place for everything and everything in its place” and here I was on a farm with a very busy husband and no one else to do lawn mowing, car washing, gardening, keeping a house clean, canning, etc…but me! But I guess eventually I learned that I was happy because I have always loved to take care of a house; cooking wasn’t my favorite thing but doing housework I loved. I always dreamed how nice it would be to live next door to a neighbor who disliked housework but loved to cook and then we could trade off…I would do all her housework and she could do all the cooking! (Of course it never could happen that way!)<br /><br />

            The farmhouse had a kitchen, dining room, living room, three bedrooms and a bath and a full basement. A fruit room, extra bedroom and furnace room and a big extra room were in the basement along with a huge monster of a coal furnace. It was scary to go into the furnace room as in those days the furnace was huge, black, noisy…and had to be fed coal! I did not enjoy going down that basement, but that’s where I did the washing and then hauled the baskets of laundry upstairs to be taken outside to the clothesline to dry; in the winter, the clothes were often frozen solid. Then when they were finally dry, maybe the next day, I would bring them in and sprinkle them down, roll them up, put them in a basket and the next day to be ironed.


            </span>

