                    I remember hours on end sitting on a stool of some sort in the spud cellar cutting seed spuds to be planted. Usually there was someone else helping as well. It was quite dark down there and damp and very cool. I often took a small radio with me for the music and company. We also hired “spud cutters” to help when we were planting and raising 30 to 40 acres of spuds. I didn’t like to cut seed potatoes! We would sit at a contraption that had a board ledge with a cutting knife inserted into it. We would feed the blade either out or in, so we would move our hands holding the spud through the knife once or twice to get the right size and then they would drop into the spud sack to be filled and then taken out and loaded into the planter. <br /><br />

                        It was always one of my least favorite kinds of work needed to be done at that farm, (never did like the smell of a spud cellar!). When we sold the farm and moved to Rexburg, the people at the farm took the cellar out and filled a landmark in the space. Not too many spud cellars still exist today because most families do not raise potatoes anymore, it’s too costly and needs huge machinery crop. Now farmers who raise potatoes do so by the hundreds, with huge machinery to do the planting, cultivating and harvesting (they are welcome to it so far as I am concerned!). When we were growing potatoes. they had to be harvested in the fall by hand picking, walking up and down the rows that had been dug out, with the potatoes lying in a row. We had to walk along with baskets and dump them, then move on to the next bucket. <br /><br />

                        It’s also very difficult to find spud pickers. For a year or two, when it was very hard to get help, Ken and Ray would go down to the employment center in Idaho Falls and try to hire help. I remember that they even went to the pool halls to find guys who were willing to come work. I had these guys—not very savory characters!—to feed and even had some of them sleeping over in the basement of our house, and then we fed them three meals a day! Horrors, that is what it was. We didn’t do that for many years. We just got tired of doing all that just to harvest the spuds and then not get enough money when we sold the crop to barely pay for expenses. I remember Ken often saying, “If we can get $3.50 a sack for the spuds we will do really well.” (We never did!) We quit raising potatoes and began to increase our cattle herd which is what Ken wanted most to do. <br /><br />

                        Ken planned in the future to have a sizable herd of cattle. He always liked to work with cattle and was very good at judging good cattle. At one time we had a sizable herd of sheep but they were never a favorite of ours. I do remember having newborn lambs brought into my kitchen and put in a warm oven to save their life. Often twins or triplet lambs would arrive and we would do our utmost to save them all! <br /><br />

                        There is a line in Ken’s patriarchal blessing that tells him that he will never be without food or raiment. When I read that blessing for the first time I thought to myself what a fantastic and wonderful promise to give to someone, but in later years, I came to realize that those promises given in a patriarchal blessing are just guidelines for our lives and we must get busy and live and work so they will happen. I am sure that Ken has used those lines in his blessing as a guide for his life for he has always been an extremely hard worker and true, we were never without plenty of food in our storage room and we always had clothes to provide for the children as well as a good home and other necessities of life and this was true because we both worked hard those years at the farm are proof of the promised blessings in the patriarchal blessing given to Ken. <br /><br />

                        I might mention here as well that when I received my blessing after Ken and I were married that those same promised were in my blessing as well. Our farmhouse in Milo was one of the largest and nicest in the whole area we had a big front porch and front lawn with lots of big trees around. Also had an orchard to the side of the house for apples and pears (that never would be eatable much to Ken’s chagrin—he loved pears). Also had an irrigation ditch in front of the house to flood water the lawn. We had a garden to the north of the house and at one time had a beautiful raspberry patch that was fertilized so well that we had the largest raspberries in the neighborhood! <br /><br />

                        The kids would love to play on the lawn when it was being irrigated. The farmhouse was white and framed, and after a few years we had to put on a new roof and we chose pink bartile for the job which is still there and still looks really good. The bedrooms in the house were really small; the front bedroom was planned primarily by Grandpa Bird as an office room and then later a bedroom. There was a diagonal arch between the living and dining rooms, the first and only house where I had a dining room! The door to the basement opened into the kitchen. I remember doing a lot of painting of that kitchen through the years. I also remember when we had the front room and living room carpeted wall to wall—such luxury! <br /><br />

                        That old furnace provided good heat for the whole house as the heat vents were large and the heat really came out But coal heat is dirty heat and we had to clean and paint quite frequently. My memories of that house are warm it was a lovely home to bring our babies to. All six were born while we lived in that house; so many warm and beautiful memories of children playing in the yard, and boys being called to help do the chores. The first freezer we had, a big—a huge—Amana freezer that we installed on the back porch. What a revolution that was for our farm living, and a whole new way of preserving food and a luxury for sure. <br /><br />

                        The farmhouse had hardwood floors that were either bare or had linoleum on them when we moved into it. The carpet we chose to put down was a blue carpet and was only put in the living and dining rooms. We painted the walls a deep aqua color (dark was “in” then). The walls throughout the whole house was rough plastered which I didn’t care for and always wanted what I couldn’t have in that house: wallpaper. And now after all these years that have passed, two of the homes we have built, the one in 1969 in Rexburg and the house in Rigby, have rough plaster all throughout the house (ah, fashion, we are thy slaves!).<br /><br />

                        There are so many happy memories of the farm. Lots of wonderful Saturday nights when the house was all clean for Sunday, the children bathed and in their pajamas and newly baked bread sitting on the cupboard and a roast thawing for Sunday dinner. Those happy times when the kids were little and so much fun to watch them growing up. That spring Ken began earnestly to farm. He owned 80 acres when we were married and we were buying the adjoining 80 acres from his dad. He always liked to have me go with him whatever he was doing and I spent lots of time riding the tractor with him before Mike was born that summer. <br /><br />

                        That summer we also bought a number of baby chicks which we ordered from a catalog or whatever. We had to go to pick them up from somewhere but I can’t remember where but we had ordered them. When they arrived we put them into a “brooder” in the basement bedroom and there took care of them until they were big enough to sell as “pullets” which were then able to be sold to a local store, more than likely a Safeway store in Idaho Falls. The chicken we had to eat was the best I can ever remember. I can remember that my first washing machine was a double tub Philco, at least I think that was the name. Philco was a big name in appliances, and in radios as well and later on television. A double tub washer was quite a luxury in those days. It was in the basement of course! Also had twin tubs for rinsing. I can still picture myself in that basement standing before the washer and rinse tubs to do the weeks washing. 
