                    My pregnancy with Mike was not a difficult one and I was only nauseated for the first three months. Never did I actually throw up. I gained 20 pounds and continued to go to Idaho Falls to Dr. West. On the day before Mike was born, Uncle Jack had come over to help kill the chickens that were of size to be sold. Uncle Jack was helping me because Ken was busy in the fields. All that afternoon the little pains were nagging, even though two weeks early I told Uncle Jack that the “baby would come tonight ” and he laughed, not believing me. Sure enough, that night a little baby boy was born after not too much labor, on Tuesday, July 13th about 3:15 in the morning. He was beautiful, lots of black hair and a little round, fat face. Ken chose the name for him and he was named Kenneth Michael Bird. He weighed 7 lb. 13 oz. and was 20.5 inches long. He was really a beautiful little guy and grew and developed into such a handsome baby; people often stopped me in the stores or along the street and comment on such a beautiful baby—made my day! <br /><br />

                    I remember Mom and Dad coming out to the farm to help with canning of peaches in September, that fall. And my dad was just absolutely smitten with Mike and he was always the favorite of his Grandpa Ingram. Dad would call on the phone and if I hadn’t had Mike into his place for a couple of days he would scold us to “bring that baby in here!” We have some cute pictures of Mike and his Grandpa Ingram.  <br /><br />

                    Mike contracted pneumonia when he was 10 months old and we had him in the hospital for a few days. I lost quite a bit of weight after that first pregnancy; I got down to 111 lbs after Mike was born and never did ever have much of a weight problem. Always have been quite thin. Mike nursed well and was a good eater as well. He grew and developed normally. I remember when he was one year old and he put his hands right in the middle of his first birthday cake. He also would come over to the kitchen sink after he learned to walk and would say “bitesey, bitesey, bitesey,” which meant, of course, that he wanted a drink of water! <br /><br />

                    Mike was a good baby and a joy to have and love. I remember that he was the only baby that I accidentally stuck with a safety pin putting on a diaper. I also remember when we brought him home from the hospital that I worried and fussed over him as if I had never held a baby before in my life! (I had spent the last six months of my training in the newborn nursery at VMH but it didn’t help much when it came to my own baby!)  <br /><br />

                    I used to wake up over every little sound he would make at night, afraid he would suffocate, or choke or some terrible thing would happen to him. He took his time sleeping throughout the whole night. As he got to be about eight or nine months old his hair was quite blonde and quite curly and we used to put a curl right on top of his head (pictures to prove) and much to his chagrin now. He was quite a darling baby boy. I was in the LDS hospital in Idaho Falls when Mike was born, and stayed there six days and the hospital bill was $78! 
