            Although I found living on a farm to be difficult sometimes, because the work was so hard, I have a lot of happy memories of that farm in Milo. The atmosphere that we lived in was good. We had wholesome activities that we participated in, not only as a family but in our ward, the Milo Ward. <br /><br />

            Kenneth was an example of a good father. He taught his boys. His boys worked along with him. Kenneth always wanted to have someone go with him as he was going out to do chores or doing field work. He wanted someone with him, and he would often take some of the children in the car if he was going on an errand or had some light work to do in the field. He always wanted to have someone to go with him. I usually was that one. When we were first married, I would go out with him often to help with the chores and maybe ride on the tractor. He loved to have someone with him. <br /><br />

            He was an example of a good father. He taught his children how to work hard. They learned hard work, especially the four boys. They had chores to do. I don’t know how willingly they did them, but they all turned out pretty good. Those boys are all hard workers now. From what they learned, I attribute that a lot to their experiences as we lived on the farm. <br /><br />

            Another thing: each one of those four boys, as they went into the mission field, wrote back to their dad a special letter and thanked him for teaching them how to work, because it was invaluable for them in the mission field.<br /><br />

            Another thing that Kenneth did was make sure that we had time to attend the temple. The first few years that we lived on the farm, we tried to attend the temple weekly when it was possible for us to do so. Our boys always were able to do the chores so we could leave and go to the temple that evening. We had other friends who had boys the same age as ours, but they didn’t have the responsibility that our boys had. Often, when we would go pick up our friends to go to the temple, we would have to wait while they finished the chores, because the boys didn’t accept that responsibility. We were proud and happy that our boys had been taught to accept that responsibility. <br /><br />

            We also had good times together when we had activities and when we took little trips with our family. We would go to Yellowstone and we would do camping trips. That was one of our funnest things to do. Oftentimes we couldn’t all go at the same time. Sometimes a couple of the boys would have to stay home and look after the chores and the animals while the rest of us would go, but mostly we tried to do those things together as a family.<br /><br />

            Our home in Milo was a very pleasant home. It was a large home. Kenneth’s father had built that home a number of years ago, but it was a modern home, very comfortable. In fact, it was one of the finest homes in the valley on the farms at that time. Kenneth was a good provider of whatever was required for us. Many of the enjoyable times we had, he provided for us as a father.<br /><br />

            As I think back on some of the experiences we had while we were living at the farm, I think the number one important thing was we, as a family, were involved in the Church and church activities, and our friends were all members of the Church. Our activities were centered in gospel-based entertainment. We had some wonderful friends in the Milo Ward, and we enjoyed being with them. Their standards were the same as ours.<br />

            </span>

